{"metadata":{"modules":[{"name":"SwiftGodot"}],"role":"article","title":"Signals","roleHeading":"Article"},"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Signals","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"variants":[{"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}],"paths":["\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/signals"]}],"sections":[],"abstract":[{"text":"Signals in Godot are used by objects to post interesting events that are","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"taking place, and can be used by users to easily add behavior and react"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"to changes."}],"primaryContentSections":[{"content":[{"level":2,"type":"heading","text":"Overview","anchor":"Overview"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Objects in Godot can emit signals, these are notification about certain"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"events taking place in the objects that can be observed externally."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In SwiftGodot, there is a convenient interface to connect to a signal, as well"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"as a low-level framework to manually connect to signals and a mechanism to"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"define your own signals."}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Objects that emit signals typically do so by using the "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Object\/emit(signal:)","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":""},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"method (or the lower-level "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Object\/emitSignal(signal:_:)"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"function) which takes as a parameter the ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/StringName","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" of the signal as well","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"as an optional list of additional arguments.   And users can connect to those","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"signals and direct a method to be invoked when they are raised."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"text":"Using Signals","anchor":"Using-Signals","type":"heading","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"To connect to a signal, find the signal that you want to connect to in your","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"type, and then call the connect method on it."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"For example, to connect to the ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Node\/ready","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" signal, you call its connect","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"method, like this:","type":"text"}]},{"syntax":"swift","code":["func setupBot (robot: Node) {","    robot.ready.connect {","        print (\"The robot's node is ready\")","    }","}"],"type":"codeListing"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Since signals in Godot can include parameters, each signal in Godot"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"surfaces a connect method that takes as an argument a function with the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"precise signature that it will be invoked with."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"If you want to stop receiving notifications, you can disconnect from the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"object, to do so, you must keep around the token returned by the connect","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"method, like this:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["class Demo: Node {","    var readyToken: Object","","    func setup () {","        readyToken = robot.ready.connect {","            print (\"Ready\")","        }","    }","","    func teardown () {","        robot.ready.disconnect (readyToken)","    }","}"]},{"anchor":"One-shot-signals","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"One-shot signals"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"One common idiom in Godot code is to wait for a signal to be raised before"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"continuing execution.   For example, you might want to wait for a timeout"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"or an action."}]},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"In those cases, you can await the ","type":"text"},{"code":"emitted","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" property of the generated"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"signal, like this:","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"code":["func waitTimer (scene: SceneTree) async {","    \/\/ Creates the timer","    let timer = scene.createTimer (timeSec: 3)","","    \/\/ Wait until the timer fires","    await timer.timeout.emitted","","    print (\"Done waiting!\")","}"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"If you do not have an async function, you can await your signal with"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"the following idiom:","type":"text"}]},{"syntax":"swift","code":["func waitSomething (scene: SceneTree) {","    \/\/ Creates a task, but executes on the main actor","    Task { @MainActor in","        await timer.timeout.emitted","        print (\"happy on the main thread\")","    }    ","}"],"type":"codeListing"},{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Declaring-your-own-Signals","text":"Declaring your own Signals"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"It is also possible to define your own signals to broadcast them, both","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"to other Swift component as well as using them in Godot or from the"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"Godot Scripting language.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Signals belong to your class, so you need to declare those once per class,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"and then every instance of your class can emit them.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Signals can have zero or more parameters, and you will need to declare","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"the parameters that your signal consumes, any potential return values (these"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"are quite unusual, but the API supports it), and the name of your signal.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"level":3,"type":"heading","anchor":"Signals-with-no-parameters","text":"Signals with no parameters"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The following example shows how to declare a a signal named ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"burp"},{"type":"text","text":" that"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"is emitted by your code:"}]},{"code":["@Godot","class Demo: Node3D {","    #signal(\"burp\")","","    \/\/ Convenience method to emit the signal","    public func emitBurp () {","        emit(Demo.burp)","    }","}"],"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The free-standing macro ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"#signal"},{"type":"text","text":" declares a signal named burp.   This macro"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"will turn signals using the snake-case naming convention into camel-case"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"names accessible in Swift.","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"So for example if you were to declare a signal called ‘lives_changed’ it"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"would be exposed to Godot as ‘lives_changed’, and to your Swift code as","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"‘livesChanged’.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"text":"Signals with parameters","type":"heading","anchor":"Signals-with-parameters","level":3},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Signals can carry additional information when they are emitted, and"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"you can pass any type that can be encoded as a Godot Variant to them"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"(this includes Swift core types like integers, doubles, strings, but","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"also Godot objects and the Godot core types;   See the documentation","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"for "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Variant","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":" for more information)."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"To use signals with parameters, you need to declare the parameter","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"types using the ","type":"text"},{"code":"arguments:","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" parameter, specifying the Swift type","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"of each parameter."}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In the following example we create a signal exposed to godot called"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"lives_changed"},{"type":"text","text":" that takes an integer value, and it is surfaced to Swift as"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"the signal ‘livesChanged’.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The example below also shows how to emit the signal with the additional","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"integer payload:","type":"text"}]},{"code":["@Godot ","class Player: Node2D {","    #signal(\"lives_changed\", argument: [\"new_lives_count\": Int.self])","","    func startGame() {","       emit(Player.livesChanged, 5)","    }","}"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift"},{"level":2,"anchor":"Connecting-Everything-Together","type":"heading","text":"Connecting Everything Together"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This example shows how you can create a signal and connect to it:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["@Godot ","class Player: Node2D {","    #signal(\"game_started\")","    #signal(\"lives_changed\", argument: [\"new_lives_count\": Int.self])","","    func startGame() {","        \/\/ No arguments","        emit(Player.gameStarted)","","        \/\/ One argument of type int","        emit(Player.livesChanged, 5)","    }","}","","class Level: Area2D {","    func _ready() { ","       player.connect(Player.gameStarted, to: self, method: \"game_started\")","       player.connect(Player.livesChanged, to: self, method: \"myLivesChanged\")","    }","","    @Callable func myLivesChanged (newLivesCount: Int) {","        print (\"New lives: \\(newLivesCount)\")","    }","","    @Callable func game_started() { ","       GD.print(\"got game started signal!\")","    }","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"text":"Low-Level Signal API","type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Low-Level-Signal-API"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This section is here for explanation purposes, but you should not need"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"to use this in your Godot code with Swift."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"anchor":"Using-the-low-level-Signal-framework","text":"Using the low-level Signal framework","type":"heading","level":3},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"While SwiftGodot provides a convenient way of connecting to objects,","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"if you need to connect to objects that are not included in the binding"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"or you want to implement additional semantics, you can always use the"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"low-level API for connecting signals.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"To connect a signal directly, you use the ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Object\/connect(signal:callable:flags:)","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"method.   The first parameter is the ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/StringName","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" describing the signal"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"and the second one is refenrece to the method to invoke.  The "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Callable"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"is a pair of the object instance and the "},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/StringName"},{"text":" of the method to invoke.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"For example:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let callable = Callable(object: self, method: StringName (\"MyCallback\"))","object.connect(signal: \"some_signal\", callable)"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"This would call a method registered with Godot under the name ","type":"text"},{"code":"MyCallback","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"on the provided instance when the ","type":"text"},{"code":"object","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" raises the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"some_signal"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To surface a Swift method to Godot, and thus be able to reference it with"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"a StringName, you would use a similar method to register a signal:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"syntax":"swift","code":["func mySwiftCallback () {","   print (\"MyCallback has been invoked!\")","}","","func setup () {","    classInfo.registerMethod(","        name: \"MyCallback\", ","        flags: .default, ","        returnValue: nil, ","        arguments: [], ","        function: Demo.mySwiftCallback)","}"],"type":"codeListing"},{"level":3,"type":"heading","text":"Emitting Signals","anchor":"Emitting-Signals"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Object\/emit(signal:)"},{"type":"text","text":" family of methods is a high-level version"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"that provides some of the boilerplate information for you, and also"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"conveniently allows you to call the emit method with any type that implements"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"the "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/VariantStorable","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"text":" protocol.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"It is quite convenient to use as you do not need to wrap your parameters in"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"Variants","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" nor provide the "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PropInfo"},{"type":"text","text":" elements for your signal definition."}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"When you declare signals using the #signal macro, you can trivially use this path."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Sometimes you might need to emit a signal on a foreign object, to pretend the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"object triggered that signal.  I will not pass any judgement on this, I merely"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"want to empower you to get the job done."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In those situations, you might still want to use the convenience emit method, over"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"emitSignal"},{"text":" version.   But you will find that you can not just call the method","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"with the signal name as you did before.","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In those cases, you will need to provide both the signal name, and the argument"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"names, like this:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"code":["let foreign: Node","","foreign.emit(signal: SignalWith1Argument(\"open\", argument1Name: \"path\"), \"\/tmp\/demo\")"],"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The ","type":"text"},{"code":"signal","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" parameter is not a plain ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/StringName","type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":", instead it takes one of the"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"SignalWithArgument types to specify the names of the arguments."}]}],"kind":"content"}],"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot"]]},"schemaVersion":{"minor":3,"patch":0,"major":0},"kind":"article","seeAlsoSections":[{"title":"Articles and Tutorials","generated":true,"identifiers":["doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Differences","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Variants","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Exports","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/CustomTypes","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/BindingNodes","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/RunningInEditor"]}],"references":{"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Exports":{"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"In Godot, class members can be exported. This means their value gets saved along"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"with the resource (such as the scene) they’re attached to. They will also be","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"available for editing in the property editor. Exporting is done by using the"}],"title":"Exports","type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/exports","kind":"article","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Exports","role":"article"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/PropInfo":{"role":"symbol","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/propinfo","type":"topic","abstract":[{"text":"PropInfo structures describe arguments to signals, and methods as well as return values from methods.","type":"text"}],"fragments":[{"text":"struct","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"PropInfo","kind":"identifier"}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PropInfo","kind":"symbol","navigatorTitle":[{"text":"PropInfo","kind":"identifier"}],"title":"PropInfo"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Object/connect(signal:callable:flags:)":{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Object\/connect(signal:callable:flags:)","title":"connect(signal:callable:flags:)","role":"symbol","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Connects a "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"signal"},{"type":"text","text":" by name to a "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"callable"},{"type":"text","text":". Optional "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"flags"},{"text":" can be also added to configure the connection’s behavior (see ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Object\/ConnectFlags","isActive":true},{"text":" constants).","type":"text"}],"fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"func"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"connect"},{"kind":"text","text":"("},{"text":"signal","kind":"externalParam"},{"kind":"text","text":": "},{"kind":"typeIdentifier","text":"StringName","preciseIdentifier":"s:10SwiftGodot10StringNameC"},{"text":", ","kind":"text"},{"kind":"externalParam","text":"callable"},{"text":": ","kind":"text"},{"kind":"typeIdentifier","text":"Callable","preciseIdentifier":"s:10SwiftGodot8CallableC"},{"text":", ","kind":"text"},{"kind":"externalParam","text":"flags"},{"text":": ","kind":"text"},{"kind":"typeIdentifier","preciseIdentifier":"s:s6UInt32V","text":"UInt32"},{"text":") -> ","kind":"text"},{"preciseIdentifier":"s:10SwiftGodot0B5ErrorO","text":"GodotError","kind":"typeIdentifier"}],"kind":"symbol","type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/object\/connect(signal:callable:flags:)"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/StringName":{"kind":"symbol","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/stringname","type":"topic","navigatorTitle":[{"text":"StringName","kind":"identifier"}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/StringName","fragments":[{"text":"class","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"StringName","kind":"identifier"}],"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"A built-in type for unique strings."}],"role":"symbol","title":"StringName"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot":{"kind":"symbol","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot","title":"SwiftGodot","role":"collection","type":"topic","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Framework to write Godot Game Extensions using the Swift Programming Language."}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/BindingNodes":{"kind":"article","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/BindingNodes","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/bindingnodes","title":"Referencing Nodes from your Scene","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"You will find yourself referencing nodes from a scene in your code.   In GDScript, that is usually"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"achieved by using the dollar sign and the name of the object you want to reference."}],"type":"topic","role":"article"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Variants":{"title":"Variants","type":"topic","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Variants","kind":"article","role":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Follow up on the fundamental building block of Godot’s data types."}],"url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/variants"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Differences":{"type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/differences","title":"SwiftGodot API differences to GDScript","role":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"This document lists some common differences between GDSscript and SwiftGodot."}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Differences","kind":"article"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Callable":{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Callable","title":"Callable","role":"symbol","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/callable","abstract":[{"text":"A built-in type representing a method or a standalone function.","type":"text"}],"type":"topic","kind":"symbol","fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"class"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"Callable","kind":"identifier"}],"navigatorTitle":[{"kind":"identifier","text":"Callable"}]},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/VariantStorable":{"kind":"symbol","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/VariantStorable","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/variantstorable","type":"topic","fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"protocol"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"VariantStorable","kind":"identifier"}],"navigatorTitle":[{"text":"VariantStorable","kind":"identifier"}],"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Types that conform to VariantStorable can be stored in a Variant and can be extracted"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"back out of a Variant."}],"title":"VariantStorable","role":"symbol"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Node/_ready()":{"title":"_ready()","kind":"symbol","abstract":[{"text":"Called when the node is “ready”, i.e. when both the node and its children have entered the scene tree. If the node has children, their ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Node\/_ready()","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" callbacks get triggered first, and the parent node will receive the ready notification afterwards."}],"url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/node\/_ready()","type":"topic","fragments":[{"text":"func","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"_ready","kind":"identifier"},{"kind":"text","text":"()"}],"role":"symbol","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Node\/_ready()"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Object/ConnectFlags":{"type":"topic","title":"Object.ConnectFlags","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Object\/ConnectFlags","role":"symbol","fragments":[{"text":"struct","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"kind":"identifier","text":"ConnectFlags"}],"abstract":[],"url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/object\/connectflags","kind":"symbol","navigatorTitle":[{"text":"ConnectFlags","kind":"identifier"}]},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/CustomTypes":{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/CustomTypes","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/customtypes","type":"topic","title":"Using Custom Types","kind":"article","role":"collectionGroup","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"You will typically extend the functionality of your Godot game by creating"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"classes that derive from one of the various Godot types and adjust the"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"behavior accordingly.","type":"text"}]},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Object/emit(signal:)":{"title":"emit(signal:)","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Object\/emit(signal:)","role":"symbol","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Emits a signal that was previously defined with the #signal macro."}],"fragments":[{"text":"func","kind":"keyword"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"text":"emit","kind":"identifier"},{"kind":"text","text":"("},{"text":"signal","kind":"externalParam"},{"kind":"text","text":": "},{"preciseIdentifier":"s:10SwiftGodot21SignalWithNoArgumentsV","text":"SignalWithNoArguments","kind":"typeIdentifier"},{"kind":"text","text":") -> "},{"text":"GodotError","kind":"typeIdentifier","preciseIdentifier":"s:10SwiftGodot0B5ErrorO"}],"kind":"symbol","type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/object\/emit(signal:)"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/RunningInEditor":{"kind":"article","title":"Running Code in the Godot Editor","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/runningineditor","type":"topic","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/RunningInEditor","role":"article","abstract":[{"text":"There are cases where you might want some of your Swift code for your extension","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"to run while it is being used in the Godot Editor."}]},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Node/ready":{"type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/node\/ready","abstract":[{"text":"Emitted when the node is ready. Comes after ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Node\/_ready()","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" callback and follows the same rules.","type":"text"}],"kind":"symbol","fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"var"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"ready","kind":"identifier"},{"text":": ","kind":"text"},{"kind":"typeIdentifier","preciseIdentifier":"s:10SwiftGodot12SimpleSignalC","text":"SimpleSignal"}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Node\/ready","title":"ready","role":"symbol"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Variant":{"fragments":[{"text":"class","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"Variant","kind":"identifier"}],"url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/variant","title":"Variant","kind":"symbol","role":"symbol","type":"topic","navigatorTitle":[{"text":"Variant","kind":"identifier"}],"abstract":[{"text":"Variant objects box various Godot Objects, you create them with one of the","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"constructors, and you can retrieve the contents using the various extension","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"constructors that are declared on the various types that are wrapped."}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Variant"}}}